  "prompt": "Is there a database of retail grocery prices?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several databases and resources that provide information on retail grocery prices. Some of the more notable ones include:\n\n1. **USDA Economic Research Service (ERS)**: The USDA provides data on food prices, including the Food Price Outlook and retail price reports, which analyze various food categories and their price fluctuations.\n\n2. **NielsenIQ**: They offer market research data on consumer goods, including grocery prices. Their data can help understand price trends in supermarkets.\n\n3. **IRI (Information Resources, Inc.)**: Similar to Nielsen, IRI provides insights and data analytics related to grocery prices and consumer behavior.\n\n4. **Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS)**: The BLS publishes the Consumer Price Index (CPI) data, which includes price changes for grocery items over time.\n\n5. **Local Grocery Stores and Chains**: Many grocery store chains have their own databases, either online or through apps, where consumers can find current pricing for items.\n\n6. **Market Basket Studies**: Some universities and local government agencies conduct regular market basket studies to track prices of staple goods across different retailers.\n\n7. **Price Comparison Websites**: Websites and apps that allow consumers to compare prices between different grocery stores in their area can be useful for obtaining up-to-date pricing.\n\n8. **Mobile Apps**: Various mobile applications focus on price tracking and grocery shopping help by allowing users to see prices at different local stores.\n\nFor specific research or governmental reports, checking the official websites or industry publications may provide the most detailed insights.",
